<article>
    <h1>On so&#xAD;cial me&#xAD;dia</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200919/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-19"><time>2020-09-19</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRENDING</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTO: LUHAN/WEIBO</span>
    </section>

    <p>THREE YEARS AND COUNT­ING: De­spite con­stant ru­mours of a break-up, Chi­nese singer and for­mer K-pop boy band mem­ber Lu Han (right) and his Chi­nese ac­tress girl­friend Guan Xiao­tong (above) are still go­ing strong.</p>
    <p>Lu, 30, wished Guan happy birth­day on Chi­nese mi­croblog­ging site Weibo at ex­actly mid­night on Thurs­day when she turned 23.</p>
    <p>Lu has done so for the past three years.</p>
    <p>In his post, ac­com­pa­nied by Guan’s pic­ture, he said: “Happy birth­day, cheer­ful girl.”</p>
    <p>She com­mented: “Thank you, cheer­ful guy.”</p>
    <p>The cou­ple re­port­edly fell in love on the set of ro­mance drama Sweet Com­bat (2018).</p>
    <p>When they an­nounced their re­la­tion­ship in Oc­to­ber 2017, the news sent fans into such over­drive that Weibo crashed briefly af­ter traf­fic soared.</p>
    <p>The love­birds have had to bat­tle break-up ru­mours for most of their re­la­tion­ship, in­clud­ing one ear­lier this year which spec­u­lated that they had bro­ken up when they did not post any­thing ro­man­tic on so­cial me­dia for Chi­nese</p>
    <p>Valen­tine’s Day on Aug 25.</p>
    <p>Guan is known for her work on series like To Be A Bet­ter Man (2016) and more re­cently, Twenty Your Life On (2020).</p>
    <p>Lu left the South Kore­anChi­nese boy band Exo in 2014 and has been pur­su­ing a solo ca­reer in China.</p>

